    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "return_value",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Return Value",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "A physics field object. To use the field in a scene, attach it to the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnnode/1408006-physicsfield"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property of an "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnnode"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " object."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "discussion",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Discussion",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The force on an object in a vortex field is tangential to the line from the object’s position to the field’s axis and proportional to the object’s mass. (The field’s axis is a line that is parallel to its "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnphysicsfield/1388128-direction"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " vector and that passes through its center. For details, see the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnphysicsfield/1388154-offset"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property.) For example, when a vortex field’s area of effect contains many objects, the resulting scene resembles a tornado: The objects simultaneously revolve around and fly away from the field’s center."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "By default, a vortex circulates counterclockwise relative to its "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnphysicsfield/1388128-direction"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " vector. To make it circulate clockwise, set the field’s "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnphysicsfield/1388132-strength"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property to a negative value."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The default "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnphysicsfield/1388146-falloffexponent"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " value for a vortex field is "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "0.0"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", indicating that the field’s effect is constant throughout its area of effect."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
